It was just a gut feeling based on what I saw.
I looked for the clues that seemed to fit together and maybe add up to something.
I studied the clues in relation to the theft and the environment of the theft.
determining which clues were real
Try and find what a criminal would most likely do and follow that into the clues.
Reading leads and attempting to develop a consistent story
see reccurring evidence for multiple people
Start with the most concrete clues and then draw conclusions from those for sure clues.
I Looked for the person name that was used the most, which from what I seen was Steven
guessed

Trying to identify what others clues were VS mine
Just looking for clues that made sense with the other clues given
I tried to find consistent information that stood out to me the most.
I looked for clues that reinforced each other
I tried to find which traits were probably tied to which people, and which clues were likely true because they appeared so often
Thinking of what I would ask if I was the police or do if I was the thief

I followed instruction
To try to eliminate clues that weren't derived from forensic evidence, or clues that could contradict each other and be irrelevent.
I just tried to think logically.
read and compare

Trying to read through ALL the clues and solve the mystery before categorizing them
reviewing patterns
The clues that went most together were the ones I focused on.
Tried to figure amount of evidence that pointed to one person. More evidence toward one person, the more I believed they did it.

I thought about what would be required for a heist like this - scoping out the location over multiple days, a getaway car, random accidents that could have happened during the process especially with bars with alcohol consumption around, the tools needed to get inside and then away. I tried to work out a series of events and the items necessary for these actions to occur.
It was to pick leads that my team members agreed on and see if there was a coherent story
Just went with my gut.

I went with my instincts.

I tried to see which clues seemed to match up with each other. I figured the more the clues agreed with each other, the more likely they were to be true, whereas the clues that didn't seem to be backed up by any of the other clues were most likely false.
I was trying to go for evidence that had multiple clues linked to it, and the circumstances of the case. Some missing clues meant you couldn't narrow down the suspect.
